THOUGHT

I reproduced the crash with an argument longer than the fixed path buffer and confirmed it is not a later filesystem error: ASan stops immediately in `strcpy` at `compress42.c:886`. Boundary testing shows lengths 1022 and 1023 reach `stat()`/`lstat()` and fail cleanly as "File name too long", while length 1024 already overflows because `strcpy` also writes the terminating NUL into `char tempname[1024]`. The call path is `main()` collecting raw argv pointers into `filelist` at line 815, then calling `comprexx(fileptr)` at line 828, where `comprexx` blindly copies `*fileptr` into the stack array. The same function also later appends `".Z"` to `tempname` and copies/appends into global `ofname[MAXPATHLEN]`, so the local fix needs to preserve room for the terminator and for any suffix that will be appended.

ROOT CAUSE: `compress42.c:886` in `comprexx()` declares `char tempname[MAXPATHLEN]` at line 884 and then executes `strcpy(tempname, *fileptr)` with no length check. `*fileptr` is directly derived from argv or recursively constructed path strings, so an input pathname of length `MAXPATHLEN` or greater writes past the 1024-byte stack buffer, including the NUL byte at length 1024. ASan reports a write of 1101 bytes for a 1100-character name, corrupting the redzone and, without ASan, potentially adjacent stack locals / saved return state. Subsequent unbounded `strcat(tempname, ".Z")`, `strcpy(ofname, tempname)`, and `strcat(ofname, ".Z")` are related hazards if paths approach the buffer limit.

LOCAL FIX: Before copying or appending, reject pathnames that cannot fit in the destination including NUL and any required suffix. Minimal replacement at the start of `comprexx()`:

```diff
@@
        int             fdout;
        char    tempname[MAXPATHLEN];

-       strcpy(tempname,*fileptr);
+       if (strlen(*fileptr) >= sizeof(tempname)) {
+               fprintf(stderr, "%s: pathname too long\n", *fileptr);
+               exit_code = 1;
+               return;
+       }
+       strcpy(tempname, *fileptr);
        errno = 0;
```

and for suffix appends in this function, add capacity checks before `strcat`/`strcpy` into fixed buffers, e.g.:

```c
if (strlen(tempname) + 2 >= sizeof(tempname)) {
        fprintf(stderr, "%s: filename too long to append .Z\n", tempname);
        exit_code = 1;
        return;
}
strcat(tempname, ".Z");

if (strlen(tempname) + 2 >= sizeof(ofname)) {
        fprintf(stderr, "%s: filename too long to append .Z\n", tempname);
        exit_code = 1;
        return;
}
snprintf(ofname, sizeof(ofname), "%s.Z", tempname);
```

For decompression output without appending, use the same `strlen(tempname) < sizeof(ofname)` invariant or `snprintf(ofname, sizeof(ofname), "%s", tempname)` after rejecting truncation.

GLOBAL FIX: Replace raw fixed-size pathname arrays plus `strcpy`/`strcat` with a single path-building abstraction used throughout the program. For example, introduce helper functions such as `path_copy(dst, dstsz, src)` and `path_join_suffix(dst, dstsz, src, suffix)` that return failure on overflow and ban direct `strcpy`/`strcat` on pathname buffers in code review/CI (`-Werror`, static analysis, grep/checkpatch rule). Better still, store filenames as dynamically allocated strings sized from `strlen(input)+suffix_len+1` (or use `asprintf`/malloc wrappers) and pass `(char *, size_t)`/owned path objects instead of naked `char *` and global arrays. This makes buffer capacity explicit and centralizes all path length validation, preventing the entire class of stack/global fixed-buffer overflows rather than only this one copy.

